{
  "comment_text": {
    "sn1.27:1.1": "The “stream” (here <i lang='pi' translate='no'>sara</i>, otherwise <i lang='pi' translate='no'>sota</i>) is usually explained as craving (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn41.5/en/sujato#5.10'>SN 41.5:5.10</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/iti109/en/sujato#3.3'>Iti 109:3.3</a>). Or else it could be the “stream of lives” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>bhavasota</i>) as in the next sutta (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn1.28/en/sujato#2.2'>SN 1.28:2.2</a>). ",
    "sn1.27:1.2": "The “cycle” of transmigration (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>saṁsāra</i>) through endless rebirths (see <a href='https://suttacentral.net/dn15/en/sujato#22.6'>DN 15:22.6</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn22/en/sujato#42.2'>MN 22:42.2</a>). | The “streams” and the “cycle” also occur together in <a href='https://suttacentral.net/ud7.2/en/sujato#4.1'>Ud 7.2:4.1</a>. ",
    "sn1.27:2.2": "The commentary says this is Nibbāna. | A <i lang='pi' translate='no'>gādha</i> is a “ford” across a river (Rig Veda 7.60.7, 7.97.8, 10.106.9; Gopatha Brāhmaṇa 1.5.2a), a safe path on which one has a “footing” to cross the water. In this verse, the verb form <i lang='pi' translate='no'>gādhati</i> means to be “established” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>patiṭṭhita</i>) like a seed in soil, or a beam of light on a floor, or consciousness in name and form. ",
    "sn1.27:2.4": "Compare eg. <a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn22.56/en/sujato#5.3'>SN 22.56:5.3</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn22/en/sujato#42.2'>MN 22:42.2</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn109/en/sujato#9.10'>MN 109:9.10</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/ud6.8/en/sujato#5.7'>Ud 6.8:5.7</a>, and <a href='https://suttacentral.net/dn15/en/sujato#22.6'>DN 15:22.6</a>. ",
    "sn1.27:2.6": "Passages such as <a href='https://suttacentral.net/snp5.2/en/sujato#6.3'>Snp 5.2:6.3</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/dn15/en/sujato#22.6'>DN 15:22.6</a> and [dn11:85.26}() say that consciousness ceases at this point, too. "
  },
